    "### Conclusion\n",
    "This assignment successfully demonstrated the application of Polynomial Regression (Degree = 3) on the Position Salaries dataset to estimate salaries based on job position levels. The key finding is that the relationship between level and salary is highly non-linear, exhibiting exponential-like growth at higher levels. \n",
    "\n",
    "The primary difference between Linear Regression and Polynomial Regression is that Linear Regression assumes a straight-line relationship ($y = \\theta_0 + \\theta_1 x$), whereas Polynomial Regression models non-linear relationships by adding higher-order terms ($y = \\theta_0 + \\theta_1 x + \\theta_2 x^2 + ... + \\theta_d x^d$), allowing the model to fit curved patterns. \n",
    "\n",
    "The main advantage of Polynomial Regression for this dataset is its ability to capture the dramatic, non-linear salary growth at executive levels (ranks 8-10) without underfitting the lower-level positions, providing significantly higher predictive accuracy and variance explanation compared to a simple linear model."
